Choose or create your workspace folder
– Let’s say your Eclipse workspace is at
C:\Users\Student\workspace
– In Explorer, inside that folder create a new directory called
Expt5_ECommTests

Download Selenium Java client libraries
a. Open browser, go to
http://www.seleniumhq.org/download
b. Under “Selenium Client & WebDriver Language Bindings (Java)”, click the ZIP link
c. Save it as, for example,
C:\Users\Student\Downloads\selenium-java-3.141.59.zip
d. In Explorer, right-click that ZIP → Extract All… → set destination to
C:\Users\Student\workspace\Expt5_ECommTests\selenium-java
You’ll now have a folder containing:

client-combined-3.141.59.jar

client-combined-3.141.59-sources.jar

And a subfolder called libs full of other JARs

Download ChromeDriver
a. In your browser go to
https://chromedriver.chromium.org/downloads
b. Find the version that exactly matches your Chrome version (open Chrome → Menu → Help → About Chrome to check)
c. Download the appropriate ZIP (Windows 64-bit, e.g.)
d. Extract that ZIP to
C:\Users\Student\workspace\Expt5_ECommTests\drivers
so you end up with
C:\Users\Student\workspace\Expt5_ECommTests\drivers\chromedriver.exe

Create the Eclipse project and link the JARs
a. Launch Eclipse, point it at C:\Users\Student\workspace as your workspace.
b. File → New → Java Project → name: Expt5_ECommTests → Finish.
c. In the Project Explorer, right-click the project → New → Folder → name it libs.
d. Also create a folder drivers the same way.
e. In Explorer, copy all .jar files from
C:\Users\Student\workspace\Expt5_ECommTests\selenium-java\ and its libs subfolder into
...\Expt5_ECommTests\libs\
f. Copy chromedriver.exe into ...\Expt5_ECommTests\drivers\.

Add those JARs to your build path
a. In Eclipse Project Explorer, right-click Expt5_ECommTests → Build Path → Configure Build Path…
b. Go to the Libraries tab → Add JARs…
c. Expand your project → select every JAR under libs → OK → Apply and Close.
d. Now Eclipse knows about all Selenium dependencies.

Verify setup
a. Right-click project → Properties → Java Build Path → Libraries
b. You should see entries for every Selenium JAR.
c. In Package Explorer, expand Referenced Libraries – you should see them listed.

Step-by-step detail for “Create four test classes under package expt5”:

In Eclipse, inside Expt5_ECommTests → src
a. Right-click src → New → Package → enter expt5 → Finish.

Create LoginTest.java
a. Right-click expt5 → New → Class → Name: LoginTest → tick “public static void main…” → Finish.
b. In the editor, replace with:

java
Copy
Edit
package expt5;

import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

public class LoginTest {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
    // point to ChromeDriver in your project
    System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver",
        System.getProperty("user.dir") + "\\drivers\\chromedriver.exe");
    WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
    driver.get("https://www.amazon.com/");
    // open sign–in
    driver.findElement(By.id("nav-signin-tooltip")).click();
    // enter email
    driver.findElement(By.id("ap_email"))
          .sendKeys("dummyuser@example.com");
    driver.findElement(By.id("continue")).click();
    // wait for the password field
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    boolean hasPassword = driver.findElements(By.id("ap_password")).size() > 0;
    System.out.println(hasPassword
        ? "✅ Login navigation OK"
        : "❌ Login navigation FAILED");
    driver.quit();
  }
}
c. Save (Ctrl+S).

Create ProductBrowsingTest.java
a. Right-click expt5 → New → Class → ProductBrowsingTest → Finish.
b. Paste:

java
Copy
Edit
package expt5;

import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.Keys;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

public class ProductBrowsingTest {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
    System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver",
        System.getProperty("user.dir") + "\\drivers\\chromedriver.exe");
    WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
    driver.get("https://www.amazon.com/");
    // search for “headphones”
    driver.findElement(By.id("twotabsearchtextbox"))
          .sendKeys("headphones" + Keys.ENTER);
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    boolean foundResults = driver.findElements(
      By.cssSelector(".s-main-slot .s-result-item")).size() > 0;
    System.out.println(foundResults
        ? "✅ Search results shown"
        : "❌ No search results");
    driver.quit();
  }
}
c. Save.

Create ShoppingCartTest.java
a. New → Class → ShoppingCartTest → Finish.
b. Paste:

java
Copy
Edit
package expt5;

import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

public class ShoppingCartTest {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
    System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver",
        System.getProperty("user.dir") + "\\drivers\\chromedriver.exe");
    WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
    driver.get("https://www.amazon.com/");
    // search and click first result
    driver.findElement(By.id("twotabsearchtextbox"))
          .sendKeys("book" + org.openqa.selenium.Keys.ENTER);
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    driver.findElement(By.cssSelector(".s-main-slot .s-result-item"))
          .click();
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    // add to cart
    driver.findElement(By.id("add-to-cart-button")).click();
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    boolean inCart = driver.findElements(
      By.id("hlb-view-cart-announce")).size() > 0;
    System.out.println(inCart
        ? "✅ Item added to cart"
        : "❌ Add to cart FAILED");
    driver.quit();
  }
}
c. Save.

Create CheckoutProcessTest.java
a. New → Class → CheckoutProcessTest → Finish.
b. Paste:

java
Copy
Edit
package expt5;

import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

public class CheckoutProcessTest {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
    System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver",
        System.getProperty("user.dir") + "\\drivers\\chromedriver.exe");
    WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
    // go straight to cart
    driver.get("https://www.amazon.com/gp/cart/view.html");
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    // proceed to checkout
    driver.findElement(By.name("proceedToRetailCheckout")).click();
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    boolean checkoutPage = driver.findElements(
      By.name("address-book-entry-0")).size() > 0;
    System.out.println(checkoutPage
        ? "✅ Checkout page OK"
        : "❌ Checkout navigation FAILED");
    driver.quit();
  }
}
c. Save.

To run any test
– Right-click the class in Package Explorer → Run As → Java Application.
– Confirm Chrome opens, flows through the steps, then look at the Console for your ✅/❌ message.
